S0 = {p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q), p ∧ (q ∨ ¬r), p ∧ (q ∨ r)}

S1 = {{p ∨ q, p}, {p ∨ q, p ∨ ¬q}, {p ∨ q, q ∨ ¬r}, {p ∨ ¬q, q}, {p ∨ q, q ∨ r}}}

S2 = {p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q), p ∧ (q ∨ ¬r)} (S2 has no elements before the second cycle)

Feel free to check the application of the resolution algorithm to these sets:

For each simple disjunctive clause C1 in S0 and each simple disjunctive clause C2 in S1:
If C1 and C2 can be resolved, calculate C = dispel(C1, C2).
For example, resolve {p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q)} and {p ∨ q, p}, {p ∨ q, p ∨ ¬q}, {p ∨ q, q ∨ ¬r}, {p ∨ ¬q, q}, {p ∨ q, q ∨ r}}. The calculation results in C = p ∨ ¬q, which is not in S0 or S1. Add C to S2:
{p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q), p ∧ (q ∨ ¬r)}
For the second set of clauses, resolve in the same way and obtain C' = p ∨ ¬r. Similar to the previous calculation, C' is not in S0 or S1, so it is added to S2:
{p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q), p ∧ (q ∨ ¬r), p ∨ ¬q}
Now we apply this result to the S1 clauses, and the calculation gives C'' = p. After checking for empty clauses, we obtain:
{p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q), p ∧ (q ∨ ¬r), p ∨ ¬q, p}
So S2 contains the following set after completing the second cycle of the resolution algorithm: {p ∧ (p ∨ q), p ∧ (p ∨ ¬q), p ∧ (q ∨ ¬r), p ∨ ¬q, p}.

To calculate the output of the resolution algorithm and the number of iterations, let's analyze the conjunctive normal form first:

(p∨q)∧(p∨¬q)∧(¬p∨r)

Let's resolve each clause with each other to get the dispelled clauses (the set of all simple disjunctive clauses):

(p∨q)∧(p∨¬q) → p∨q ∨ p∨
(p∨q)∧(p∨¬q) → p∨q ∨ ¬p∨
(¬p∨r) → p∨(¬p∨) ∨ r

First iteration:
- Resolve (p∨q) ∨ p∨ β = {(p∨q) ∨ p∨, p∨q ∨ ¬p∨)}
- Resolve (p∨q) ∨ ¬p∨ β = {(p∨q) ∨ p∨, p∨q ∨ ¬p∨, p∨q ∨ r)}

Second iteration:
- Resolve (p∨q) ∨ p∨ β = {(p∨q) ∨ p∨, p∨q ∨ ¬p∨)}
- Resolve (p∨q) ∨ ¬p∨ β = {(p∨q) ∨ p∨, p∨q ∨ ¬p∨, p∨q ∨ r)}

Thus, there are two cycles. The first cycle consists of 1 contradiction (0 = p∨q ∨ ¬p∨) and the second cycle involves 2 contradictions: (p∨q) ∨ p∨ and (p∨q) ∨ ¬p∨ are both contradictions because they contain the literal p, which contradicts the implication.

The output of the resolution algorithm is: {"Implausible"}

The number of cycles is 2, since there are 2 cycles in the process of solving the conjunctive normal form. The algorithm will cycle through one set of clauses and then the other, with the hoped-for result of adding 0 to S2 in the end. This zero indicates that no satisfying assignment exists, resulting in "Implausible" as the output.

